ng can serve not just as an illustration for philosophical arguments, but also as the model for them--that painting itself has sometimes been a form of epistemological experiment, and that, perhaps surprisingly, the Neapolitan Baroque may have been one of the routes through which modern consciousness was formed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArt and philosophyzItalyxHistoryy18th century. 0aArt and philosophy. 0aMalerei. 0aPaintingxPhilosophy. 0aPainting, BaroquezItalyxNaples. 0aPainting, BaroquezItalyzNaples. 0aPainting, Baroque. 0aPainting, ItalianzItalyxNaplesy18th century. 0aPainting, ItalianzItalyzNaplesy18th century. 0aPainting, Italian. 0aTruth. 0aÄsthetik. 7aART / European.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066592540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140084974140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400849741423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400849741.jpg  a978-3-11-066592-5  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_AD  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_AD  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK